Spanish Regions and Aging in R

Aitor Alexander Gutierrez Valero

2022-08-01

GDP per capita of Spanish Regions in the year 2000 and 2019

From the Instituto National de Estadística and the Instituto Geográfico Nacional. Euros Inflation Adjusted to 2019


First, I imported data relating to Spain’s GDP per capita in 2000 and 2019, and from the “mapSpain” package I imported “pobmun19” which is a df including Spain’s 2019 census. Next, I cleaned up the GDP df in order to merge it with the census df.

ggplot(spain_gdp_sf) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = x2000),
    color = "grey50",
    lwd = .05
  ) +
  geom_sf(data = Can, color = "grey40") +
  geom_sf_label(aes(label = provincia),
    fill = "white", alpha = 0,
    size = 1.2,
    label.size = 0
  ) +
  scale_fill_gradientn(
    colors = hcl.colors(10, "Cividis", rev = TRUE),
    n.breaks = 10,
    limits = c(10000, 37000),
    guide = guide_legend(title = "GDPPC / €")
  ) +
  theme_void() +
  theme(legend.position = c(0.1, 0.6)) +
  ggtitle("Economic Growth of Spanish Provinces, 2000", subtitle = "Inflation Adjusted (2019 Euros)")

spain_gdp_sf <- spain_gdp_sf %>% #Create Absolute and Percent Columns
  mutate(Absolute = x2019-x2000,
         Percent = (x2019-x2000)/x2000*100)

ggplot(spain_gdp_sf) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = Absolute),
    color = "grey50",
    lwd = .05
  ) +
  geom_sf(data = Can, color = "grey40") +
  geom_sf_label(aes(label = provincia),
    fill = "white", alpha = 0,
    size = 1.2,
    label.size = 0,
    colour = "black"
  ) +
  scale_fill_gradientn(
    colors = hcl.colors(10, "Cividis", rev = TRUE),
    n.breaks = 10,
    guide = guide_legend(title = "Change in GDPPC / €")
  ) +
  theme_void() +
  theme(legend.position = c(0.1, 0.6)) +
  ggtitle("Economic Growth of Spanish Provinces, 2000 to 2019", subtitle = "Inflation Adjusted (2019 Euros)")
